Well, all good things have to come to an end. Besides getting old chicken the last 3 times I have been in the store, popeyes has discontinued items that I specifically went to the store for.  They introduced new items like their flounder sandwich, which *could* be good, but a cross section of the fish shows the problem immediately - too much breading. If the top and the bottom breading are each as thick as the fish, that means 2/3 of the main part of the sandwich is made of breading. Add the bun to that, and you have a big bread/carb blob with a small piece of fish tucked inside. The fish would be large enough for the sandwich if the breading was half as thick. If you can't taste the fish, the sandwich is pretty useless. The small amount of tartar sauce was absorbed by the breading, and almost wasn't noticeable. The pickles are as thick as the fish - again, the ratio is wrong. No options for lettuce, tomato, or cheese either. If they offered lettuce, tomato, and cheese on the chicken sandwich, the additions wouldn't be a problem to add to the flounder sandwich. Why is this flounder sandwich on the menu? Oh, of course - to keep lenten fasting from taking people away from Popeyes on Fridays. If the shrimp options were any good, that would have sufficed, but *no one* eats Popeyes shrimp. That is the equivalence of getting a ribeye steak at a deli.  I should have seen the writing on the wall that the jalapeno poppers were on the way out. The jalapeno poppers' signature "pepper jelly" was discontinued 6 months ago, and oddly enough, the employees were instructed to act as if there was never such a thing as this pepper jelly, even though I had purchased the jalapeno poppers with the pepper jelly from that particular store multiple times. Bizarre. Well, they don't need the pepper jelly now, because the jalapeno poppers have been discontinued also.  The real head scratcher is Popeyes discontinuing their cajun rice (dirty rice.) I've been able to get cajun rice from Popeyes since they started in Louisiana in 1972. I'm not exactly sure what they are thinking with discontinuing the cajun rice. The item is a staple that sets them aside from other restaurants. It is quintessential to coastal Louisiana cuisine, and is downright cheap to make in large quantities. I'm pretty stunned about this development. Discontinuing cajun rice is a deal breaker for me about Popeyes.  I have been tolerating getting at least 1 or 2 pieces of dry, old chicken in an order of 5 or more pieces, because I like the sides and cannot get things like the cajun rice at other places. Without the cajun rice, Popeyes is just old, dry chicken. Not a fan anymore, and won't be back. Give it a little time. Once people see their favorites gone from the menu, they won't tolerate the "come and go" quality of the chicken at Popeyes anymore either. Unless the decision to get rid of cajun rice on the menu is reversed in a timely manner, people in NYC have a long memory. Once people have concluded that their favorite menu items aren't coming back, they will write off the store completely, as if it doesn't exist. Then the customer loss will be permanent.  So sad to see Popeyes on the way out in NYC, after they just got here a couple of years ago.  ____________________________________ Early 2020:  Food always hot and fresh. Too bad the chicken sandwich is out (a testament to the great taste!) Always go to the Popeyes app and the deals will save a good deal of $. Wish the store was open later. Between 10pm and 11pm, the store becomes standing room only - seems like the demographic of the area agrees with me on the closing time.

I don't know what it is but this Popeyes has a lot of potential. I'm not really a fast food guy. I have my favorite restaurants but Popeyes has been a great experience for me recently. For starters the combo meals are amazing my signature combo is the five piece chicken tender meal, caujin fries, with extra fries, two biscuits with a side of Honey Mustard and Strawberry Jelly. That meal is probably the best combo meal I've had at a chicken restaurant easily. Flavorful chicken, well seasoned fries probably my top five favorite fries in the fast food industry, and the legendary Popeyes biscuits. Which are sometimes very buttery, flaky, and easy to bite, or very hard it can be compared to a NHL hockey puck. But in my experience in this Popeyes the biscuits are wonderful! Just add some strawberry jelly for a good time! The atmosphere is great unlike the McDonald's across street Popeye's employees take care of the riff raff that are the homeless people which is honestly the only negative. Every once in a while a homeless person would be near the door asking for change or beg for food. Which can be a little annoying but the employees jump into action and take care of it. Other than the five piece tender meal. Their Chicken Sandwich, chicken meal bucket, Gallon Lemonade, and butterfly shrimp are huge heavy hitters and are cooked and taken care of with undivided attention. I was highly impressed with most of the meals I had here and I definitely will find myself coming here more often during my commutes before work.

It doesn't happen too often, but if you can hit up a Popeye's its opening week, do it. There's nothing better that chicken fried in spanking fresh fryer grease.  There's a decent amount of seating and restrooms. If the McDonald's across the street is any indicator, it's going to be a mess by the end of next month.  The line was to the door and it took 10 mins to order, but it did just open. And it was full of kids on their lunch break. What NYC school lets kids out to lunch anymore??? I thought they quit doing that in the early 80s. The kid in front of me bought a nearly $9 nugget meal. I wonder what his allowance looks like.  The registers have a screen facing you so you can make sure your order is correct before they charge you. Whether they bag it correctly is another thing. Check your order.  Unlike the old biddies and cranks that post comments in the Westside Rag, a Popeye's at the 96th St. Station is not the end of civilization. It's a great spot to grab some of the best fried chicken, fast food or not. Especially if the oil is fresh.
